**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Our POS system has an integration to WooCommerce for updating inventory status.
Some customers might have a large number of products and product variations (20 000+)
The batch operation can manage 100 items in one request which is working very well when we handle only normal products because the url used is `/wp-json/wc/v3/products/batch`

However, if there are product variations, the url used is `/wp-json/wc/v3/products/<product_id>/variations/batch`
Because of the <product_id> part, our server have to split up this batch operation into several different requests, which will result in a huge amount of small http request. Doing this will then futher result in the woocommerce server rejecting requests because of rate limit or some other kind of protection against to many requests from same source.

I've googled quite a lot but have not been able to find any kind of plugin that solves this and I worry that it might have to do how the database is designed when it comes to product variations.


**Describe the solution you'd like**
The best solution from our point of view is to be able to perform batch operation on product variations on the same url as for normal products, `/wp-json/wc/v3/products/batch`
and the body would look like this

```
{
  "update": [
    {
      "id": 733,  <<< the product id for a normal product
      "stock_quantity": 10
    },
    {
      "id": 734,  <<< the product id for a product variation
      "variation_id": 1453,
      "stock_quantity": 10
    }
  ],
}

```

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Or the body could look like this

```
{
  "update": [
    {
      "id": 733,  <<< the product id for a normal product
      "stock_quantity": 10
    },
    {
      "id": 1453,  <<< the product variation id for a product variation
      "stock_quantity": 10
    }
  ],
}

```

Another solution would be a completely new url for mixing products and product variations.

Either way, the way product variations are handled today is not very efficient when it comes to batch operations.




